In the Purchase Orders module of Acumatica ERP, many elements on the data entry forms may have default values. If the default values you set are the values your organization uses most frequently, your users will save time and minimize errors. Users can, of course, override these values at any time. {br}
Some default settings are defined within the Purchase Orders module; others are defined in the modules that integrate closely with the Purchase Orders module: Inventory and Accounts Payable. {br}{TOC} ==Default GL Accounts== To specify the default accounts for use in the Purchase Orders module, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. These default accounts include the following ones: *Account and subaccount for freight expenses: You need to specify the account and subaccount for the freight expenses incurred in the delivery of purchased goods from vendors. Enter the appropriate '''Freight Expense Account''' and '''Freight Expense Sub.''' values. *Accounts used for purchase return operations: You can define the accounts and subaccounts used for purchase return operations by assigning a specific reason code for purchase returns in the '''PO Return Reason Code''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] form. Reason codes are defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) form.
For a detailed description of other settings that you can use to control the workflow of purchase orders and related documents, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_AffectingProcessingDocs|Changing the Processing of Purchase Documents]. ==Vendor Defaults== Once you select a vendor on a new purchase order, many elements on the order get default values. These values, specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] ([~/?ScreenId=AP303000|AP303000]) form, are used as default values on data entry forms in the Accounts Payable and Purchase Orders modules. These settings include the following: *The currency used by the vendor. The currency can be overridden on particular documents, if this is allowed by vendor settings located on the '''General Info''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] form. *The credit terms. *The shipping terms. *The vendor&rsquo;s shipping location. *The carrier used by the vendor. *The vendor&rsquo;s contact information. *The payment settings used for payments made to vendors. *GL accounts and subaccounts used to record expenses, freights, prepayments, and total liability.
A vendor&rsquo;s default settings also include the tax zone, which determines the taxes applicable to goods and services purchased from the vendor. You can also define the minimum and maximum percentage of ordered goods that can be accepted, and the actions to be performed if the ordered quantity differs from the received quantity when the quantities of received goods fall outside the specified range. ==Inventory Item Defaults== The inventory item records provide default values for purchase orders and receipts, such as the units of measure, vendor prices, and accounts involved. You can also provide the item settings associated with the specific warehouse that is used in purchase receipts created in the Purchase Orders module, and in the inventory receipts automatically generated to update the costs and availability data of the item. {br}
The default settings for stock items are defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. For more information on configuring inventory items, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__mng_Configuring_Basic_Inventory|Configuring Basic Inventory]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Landed_Cost_Tracking|Processing Landed Cost Documents] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_20_00|Landed Cost Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=PO202000|PO202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_10_10|Numbering Sequences] ([~/?ScreenId=CS201010|CS201010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_55_00|Assignment and Approval Maps] ([~/?ScreenId=EP205500|EP205500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] ([~/?ScreenId=AP303000|AP303000])

If the ''Vendor Relations'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, the vendor relations functionality can be configured. The following sections describe how the vendor relations you configure may affect the AP bills and debit adjustments created based on a purchase order or purchase receipt. ==Vendor Relations Overview== In some companies that consist of multiple branches, the branches can collectively make on order to a vendor on behalf of the company (that is, its head office) by sending purchase orders to that vendor. The supplier provides goods and issues a bill to the head office of the company. The head office pays it, and, in turn, issues bills to its branches. As a result, a branch receives goods from one vendor (specified in the purchase order), but pays for those goods to another vendor (specified in the bill). In Acumatica ERP, you can set up vendor relations so that the system accurately handles those vendor relations in documents. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] ([~/?ScreenId=AP303000|AP303000]) form, for each vendor that supplies goods and services but does not receive payment (a ''supplied-by'' vendor), you specify its vendor for which an AP bill or debit adjustment should be created if this vendor is specified in a purchase order or receipt (the pay-to vendor). For details, see [HelpRoot_Financials\AP__con_Vendor_Relations_Overview|Vendor Relations Overview]. ==Vendor Relations in Purchase Orders and Purchase Receipts== When you create a purchase order on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form, in the '''Vendor''' box of the Summary area, you can select a vendor with either vendor relations set up (a supplied-by vendor) or a vendor with no vendor relations set up. The system does one of the following for the purchase order: [anchor|#ul_zxd_2tp_f1b] *If the selected vendor is a supplied-by vendor, the system inserts in the '''Pay-to Vendor''' box of the '''Vendor Info''' tab the pay-to vendor that is specified for the selected supplied-by vendor on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] form. *If vendor relations are not configured for the selected vendor, the system inserts this same vendor in the '''Pay-to Vendor''' box of the '''Vendor Info''' tab. ((({S:Hint}For purchase receipts on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form, the system selects the '''Pay-to Vendor''' in the same way. The only difference is that this box is located on the '''Financial Details''' tab, in the '''Billing Settings''' section. ))){br}
For a purchase order or a purchase receipt, you can override the vendor in the '''Pay-to Vendor''' box, if needed.{br}
With the vendor relations functionality set up, when you invoke '''Actions &gt; Enter AP Bill''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form, the system creates an AP bill (or, for example, a debit adjustment for a purchase receipt of the ''Return'' type) on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form that has all the details copied from the initial document except the vendor in the '''Vendor''' box. In this box, the system inserts the vendor specified in the '''Pay-to Vendor''' box of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form. As a result, the bill will be paid to a different vendor than the vendor for which the purchase order was created. ==Discount Calculation== In an Accounts Payable document (bill or debit adjustment) on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form that is based on the purchase order, the system uses the discounts of the supplied-by vendor to calculate document discounts. ==Tax Calculation== For a purchase order or purchase receipt on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form with vendor relations set up, the system calculates the tax and taxable amounts of the purchase order or purchase receipt by using the tax zones of the supplied-by vendors (that is, of the vendor specified in the '''Vendor''' box of the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form). With vendor relations set up, the system calculates the tax and taxable amounts of the Accounts Payable documents similarly. {br}
If integration with Avalara AvaTax is configured and used for calculating taxes for purchase documents, the vendor relations you configure may affect the way the system selects the '''From''' and '''To''' addresses in these purchase documents. For more information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Use_Tax_PO_Avalara|Calculating Use Taxes in Purchase Documents]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Financials\AP__con_Vendor_Relations_in_AP|Vendor Relations in Accounts Payable Documents] *[HelpRoot_Financials\AP__con_Vendor_Relations_Overview|Vendor Relations Overview] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] ([~/?ScreenId=AP303000|AP303000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000])

In Acumatica ERP, you can create and maintain vendor catalogs—that is, the lists of the inventory items you purchase from each vendor, along with the last prices of items and purchasing information about the items, which are generally used for automated replenishment. By maintaining vendor catalogs, you can more efficiently select vendors that sell specific types of items. You can also reduce errors on purchase orders by using vendor-specific alternate IDs of items. {br}{TOC} ==Creating Vendor Catalogs== To create vendor catalogs, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_10_00|Vendor Inventory] ([~/?ScreenId=PO201000|PO201000]) form. On this form, you can select a vendor and vendor location and create a list of items your company can purchase from this vendor location. {br}
For each item, you can specify the following information, some of which may be specific to the vendor location: [anchor|#ul_rnd_bws_1q] *The vendor inventory ID, which is the identifier used by the vendor for the item. This alternate ID can be assigned to the item (or to the item–subitem pair if your organization uses subitems for more detailed identification of products). *The unit of measure (UOM) used by the vendor as the sales unit for the item at this location (defined as the item&rsquo;s ''purchase unit'' in your organization). *The economic order quantity, which represents the quantity of this item that minimizes the costs of ordering from this vendor location. *The vendor lead time, and the additional lead time (if any) for the inventory item purchased from the vendor. The system uses the additional lead time to schedule the purchases from the vendor and calculate the promised date. The system automatically calculates the promised date by adding the lead time and additional lead time (if any was specified for the item) to the requested date. *The purchasing information, which is used in automated replenishment: **The minimum frequency of orders. **The lot size defined for the item if it is tracked by lot numbers. **The minimum and maximum quantity that form the range in which the order quantity must fall ((({S:Hint}You cannot enter the prices in the '''Last Vendor Price''' column. The column is populated and updated automatically by the prices that were last used for the items. For details on setting up automatic price updating, see the following section. ))) Instead of entering all the items for each vendor and location, you can populate the vendor catalogs by creating a list of possible vendors for each stock item by using the '''Vendor Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form and for each non-stock item by using the same-name tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. Then, when you open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_10_00|Vendor Inventory] ([~/?ScreenId=PO201000|PO201000]) form and select a vendor, you can view the stock and non-stock items that the vendor sells and modify this list if needed. ==Catalog Updating from Vendor Documents== You can update the vendor catalogs manually at any time by replacing any changed data—such as alternate IDs, economic order quantities (EOQs), lot sizes, and minimum and maximum quantities—with the newer and more correct data. However, the last used prices in the catalogs cannot be entered manually; the system updates these prices automatically from prices quoted on vendor documents. {br}
You can set up automatic updating of the last used vendor prices in the vendor catalog based on the entry or release of specific vendor documents. To do this, on the '''Price/Discount Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_10_10_00|Accounts Payable Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AP101000|AP101000]) form, in the '''Vendor Price Update''' box, select one of the following options:[anchor|#ul_nxm_bhl_rp] *''On PO Entry'' * ''On AP Bill Release'' * ''None''
When the event specified by the '''Vendor Price Update''' option (purchase order entry, or release of an AP bill that is linked to a purchase receipt or order) occurs, the item&rsquo;s unit price from the document replaces the last price of the item with the same UOM in the vendor catalog. If the UOM of the last price is the same as in the document, but the currency differs from the document&rsquo;s currency, the item&rsquo;s unit price in the document currency replaces the last price. If the UOM in the document line differs from the UOM of the last price, the system adds a new line to the vendor catalog.((({S:Hint}The system does not keep the history of price changes in the vendor catalog. ))) If you do not want to maintain information about the last used prices in the vendor catalogs, select ''None'' as the '''Vendor Price Update''' option—the last used prices will not be updated. Note that in this case the last vendor price may be updated on release of a bill that is not linked to any PO document. ==Using the Prices from Vendor Catalogs== If you regularly receive vendors&rsquo; price lists for all or most of their items, you can maintain vendor prices with much more flexibility by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_00|Vendor Prices] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202000|AP202000]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_10|Vendor Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202010|AP202010]) forms. You can import the price lists, and calculate the updated prices by applying specific percentages. {br}
Maintaining vendor prices through vendor catalogs can also be useful for items for which the prices do not change often or information about prices is not available in advance. Once the system populates the '''Last Vendor Price''' column for items in the vendor catalogs, the system uses these last used prices as the default prices for the corresponding items on new purchase orders as follows: When you create a new purchase order on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form or receipt on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form, if there are no prices listed for the item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_00|Vendor Prices] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202000|AP202000]) form, for each item, the system inserts the last price from the vendor catalog as the vendor's default price ('''Unit Cost''' on either form). ((({S:Hint}If you are browsing the vendor catalog on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_10_00|Vendor Inventory] form in order to select a vendor for a specific item, you can view this vendor's current item prices by clicking the '''Vendor Prices''' button on the table toolbar and navigating to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_00|Vendor Prices] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202000|AP202000]) form. ))) You can override the default catalog prices on a purchase order or purchase receipt if the actual purchase prices for inventory items are different from those listed in the vendor catalog. In this case, the new prices that you enter will automatically appear in the vendor catalog as the last used prices; the particular event triggering this update depends on the option selected in the '''Vendor Price Update''' box. The new prices will then appear on a new purchase order when a user creates it. {br}
However, if the ''Volume Pricing'' feature is enabled in your system, and you purchase different volumes with different prices from your vendors, consider whether you need to maintain price updating in the catalog, taking into account that you will not know what volume the price listed in the catalog corresponds to. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Cross-References|Item Cross-References] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_10_00|Vendor Inventory] ([~/?ScreenId=PO201000|PO201000])

While barcodes have been in use in retail stores for many years, many warehouses do not fully use this technology. Barcode scanning saves you time when you receive goods to warehouses and increases overall control of operations. {br}

 Acumatica ERP supports integration with barcode scanning solutions in the following ways. {br}{TOC}
==Barcodes as Alternative IDs for Inventory Items==
In Acumatica ERP, you can use product barcodes as alternative identifiers for inventory items. For details on allowed types of alternative IDs, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Cross-References|Item Cross-References]. {br}

You can enter barcodes for items on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, the '''Cross-References''' tab, manually or by scanning them. The scanner&rsquo;s software converts the scanned barcode to an alphanumeric string that is immediately visible in the appropriate box as if it had been typed. You can add any number of different barcode strings to the item record in the database. Barcodes are not necessarily associated with particular vendors or customers. 
==Data Entry Through Barcode Scanning==
Barcode scanning can be used to effectively receive products at a warehouse and enter warehouse location information for them. {br}

From the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form, you can invoke the '''Add Receipt Line''' dialog box, which has been designed for the following scenario: You scan a product barcode, and the system finds the item record, brings up the item information with the quantity copied from a matching purchase order, and automatically adds a new line to the receipt or adds one unit per each scanned item if you scan items with serial numbers. {br}

To use the dialog box for barcode scanning, make sure the '''Add Receipt Line Automatically''' option is selected. Then, once the dialog box elements are filled in, the system creates a new line automatically. {br}

If you select the '''Add One Unit per Barcode''' check box in the dialog box, each time you scan a barcode, the item quantity for the receipt will be increased by one unit. If you clear the check box, when a user scans an item barcode, the system searches for a purchase order that matches the vendor and inventory ID associated with the barcode, and inserts the quantity of the item from the purchase order. If no such order is found, the system inserts one unit.{br}

If no item is found in the system after the item barcode has been scanned, you can enter the inventory ID of the item manually. In this case, this new barcode is automatically associated with the item. {br}

To further simplify data entry in warehouses, you can print barcodes for warehouse IDs and warehouse location IDs. You can print barcodes for such identifiers by using customized Acumatica ERP reports. {br}

Barcodes of the warehouse and its locations also can be used when you create receipts by using the following scenarios: 
*If you create receipts at a desk, print barcodes on a sheet of paper, and put it close at hand. When you&rsquo;re creating a receipt line for an item, scan the barcode from the item, warehouse, and location barcodes from the paper.
*If you generally create receipts from a cart (equipped with a scanner and a computer) after you place items in appropriate locations, perform the following actions prior to receiving goods: print location IDs as barcodes on special labels, and stick them to appropriate shelves, bins, or other storage structures available in your warehouse. Then, take items one by one from the cart, and read the item barcode and location barcode from the shelf. Appropriate receipt lines will be added automatically.

==Using Barcode Scanners for Physical Inventory==
With Acumatica ERP, you can use barcode scanners to perform physical inventory counts.{br}

If product barcodes are used in your system as alternative inventory IDs, you can use barcode scanners for counting—each scanned barcode will increase the quantity of the item by one unit in the physical inventory document open on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_10|Physical Inventory Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305010|IN305010]) if your system is configured for using barcodes and if the scanners are connected as an input device to your computer.
