To process a sale that requires the items to be shipped before an invoice can be prepared, you can use sales orders of the ''SO'' and ''SA'' predefined types. A sales order of the ''SO'' type represents a customer request to buy goods in a specified quantity on a specified date. A sales order of the ''SA'' type also represents a customer request to buy goods in a specified quantity on a particular date, but in this case, the goods are automatically reserved in inventory (that is, are allocated) for this particular order. In a typical distribution organization, the customer order may be taken over the phone or received by email.{br}

For a sales order of the ''SO'' or ''SA'' type that includes stock items and may include non-stock items requiring shipment, the typical processing involves the actions and generated documents shown in the following diagram.[anchor|#fig_p5z_bpd_h5][anchor|#image_z5v_1hn_dt][image:UserGuide/Images/Inventory_Sale_With_Shipping.png|popup|450px]((({S:Hint}If quick processing is configured for the ''SO'' or ''SA'' order type, you can perform complete processing of orders of that type directly from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. For more information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Quick_Process_Workflow|Quick Processing of Sales Orders].
)))
The following sections describe in detail the processing steps shown in the diagram.{br}{TOC}
==1. Enter the Sales Order==
You create a new sales order of the ''SO'' or ''SA'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. A reference number for a new orders are generated according to the numbering sequence assigned to this order type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_20_10_00|Order Types] form. If the order is created with the ''On Hold'' status, you should clear the '''Hold''' check box for the order to process it further. For details about the settings specified in the sales order, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_SO_OrderInfo|Sales Order Entry].
==2. Reserve Items in the Warehouse==
For an ''SA'' order the system reserves stock items in inventory automatically. For an ''SO'' order, item allocation is optional and can be performed manually by user, if needed.{br}

For a sales order of the ''SO'' type, you may choose to manually allocate (reserve) the requested quantity for a specific item or multiple items if this is required by your company policies or was requested by the customer. If you perform allocation for any item on a sales order with the ''On Hold'', ''Credit Hold'', ''Pending Approval'', ''Rejected'', or ''Open'' status, the item quantity will be added to the SO Allocated quantity shown for the item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. Also, you may want to reserve the line item if the item is available but the quantity required for the order line is distributed between different warehouses and any transfers are required.{br}

For a sales order of the ''SA'' type, once a user saves a new sales order, even with the ''On Hold'' status, the system automatically reserves the requested quantities of items for this order. On the '''Document Details''' tab, you can view the allocation for each line item and change it, if needed. by clicking a line and clicking the '''Allocations''' button. The quantities of the items that have been allocated for the order are added to SO Allocated quantities and deducted from Available for Shipping quantities (both of which are reflected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] form)—thus, these quantities cannot be shipped for another order. If the ordered quantity is available only partially and cannot be fully allocated at the specified locations, the quantity that has been allocated for the order will be added to the SO Allocated quantity, while the remaining (unallocated) quantity will be added to the SO Back Ordered quantity. You can also click the '''Actions''' > '''Place on Back Order''' action on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form to back-order the sales order until the full quantities of ordered items become available in the specified warehouse. Alternatively, you can allocate the unavailable quantity in other warehouses.
==3. Prepare the Shipment==
You can create a shipment for an individual sales order by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Create Shipment''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. Alternatively, you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_10_00|Process Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO501000|SO501000]) form to create shipments for multiple orders by executing the ''Create Shipment'' action for the selected sales orders. Each newly created shipment will have the ''Open'' status if the '''Hold Shipments on Entry''' check box is cleared on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form.{br}

The way the order will be fulfilled depends on the shipping rules specified for the order and for each line of the order on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. The shipping rule specified for a line on the '''Details''' tab defines whether the stock item should be shipped only in the full ordered quantity or the item can be shipped partially in one shipment or multiple shipments. For detailed information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipping_Rules|Shipping Rule Combinations]. {br}

If you attempt to create a shipment for an ''SA'' order before you allocate the entire quantities and if partial shipment is allowed by the specified line-level and document-level shipping rules, the system will be able to include only the allocated quantities in the shipment, even if the ordered quantities are available for shipping at another location or locations but were not allocated for the order.{br}

You can print a pick list for a particular shipment by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] form. For multiple shipments with the ''On Hold'' and ''Open'' statuses, you can print pick lists by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] form. For more details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipment_Processing|Shipment Processing Steps].((({S:Hint}To track how a sales order is being fulfilled, you can check its status and the quantities that are being shipped and not yet shipped (the '''Shipped Qty.''' and '''Open Quantity''' columns, respectively, on the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form.
)))
==4. Confirm the Shipment==
You can confirm a shipment for a particular order by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Confirm Shipment''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form, or you can confirm multiple shipments by executing the ''Confirm Shipment'' action for the selected shipments on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form. 
==5. Prepare the Sales Orders Invoice==
You can prepare a Sales Orders invoice for a particular shipment by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Prepare Invoice''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form, or you can create invoices by using the ''Prepare Invoice'' action and processing multiple selected shipments on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form. The prepared document or documents can be reviewed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_30_00|Invoices] ([~/?ScreenId=SO303000|SO303000]) form.{br}

You can print an SO invoice by clicking '''Reports &gt; Print Invoice''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_30_00|Invoices] ([~/?ScreenId=SO303000|SO303000]) form. 
==6. Release the Sales Orders Invoice==
To release the Sales Orders invoice, you click '''Actions &gt; Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_30_00|Invoices] ([~/?ScreenId=SO303000|SO303000]) form. When the SO invoice is released, a batch of General Ledger transactions is generated. {br}

When the SO invoice is released, the system automatically generates a corresponding inventory issue with the date and posting period of the invoice. If the invoice is linked to multiple shipments, the system generates a separate inventory issue for each shipment. If the invoice includes a part of the shipment, the system generates an individual inventory issue for this part. If the system cannot prepare any of the inventory issues for the invoice for some reason, the invoice release is rolled back. {br}

Also, when the SO invoice is released, a corresponding Accounts Receivable invoice is created and becomes available on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_10_00|Invoices and Memos] ([~/?ScreenId=AR301000|AR301000]) form. For more information on processing Accounts Receivable invoices, see [HelpRoot_Financials\AR__MNG_InvoicesMemos|Processing Invoices].{br}

If the ordered goods have been shipped in full according to the shipping rules, then on invoice release, the order gets the ''Completed'' status. If the order has been shipped partially, it gets the ''Back Order'' status and can be completed by additional shipments. 
==7. Release the Inventory Issue==
The generated inventory issue is released automatically if the '''Automatically Release IN Documents''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] form. If this check box is cleared, you have to release the inventory issue manually by clicking '''Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]) form.

The fulfillment of sales orders is most effective if the system displays correct information about the quantities of items that are on hand and available for shipping. In Acumatica ERP, you can reserve (also called allocate) stock when you enter sales orders so that the items promised to a customer can’t be shipped to another customer; this helps your company to avoid overstocks and stockouts of items being sold.{br}
This article describes the allocation options available for orders of the ''SA'' and ''SO'' predefined types.{br}{TOC} ==Sales Orders with Automatic Allocation (SA)== When you save an order of the ''SA'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form, the system automatically attempts to reserve the requested quantities of all line items in the specified warehouse. To view whether the entire ordered quantity of a line item has been successfully reserved, on the '''Document Details''' tab, you can click a line in the order and click '''Allocations''' on the table toolbar; then review the allocation schedule in the '''Allocations''' dialog box, which is opened. For any of the line items, if there is an insufficient quantity in the specified warehouse, the system automatically splits the requested quantity into two allocation schedules: one with the available quantity reserved in the specified warehouse, and one with the remaining quantity, for which you can select another source warehouse and reserve the remaining quantity (or a part of it) manually.((({S:Hint}If you have reserved items at multiple warehouses, the processing of the sales order requires processing a transfer order to move items from the source warehouse to the warehouse where they are needed for sale. After the transferred quantities are received to a single warehouse, you can create a shipment for the order. For a detailed description of this process, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_scn_Sale_with_Transfer|Processing Steps for a Sale with Transfer]. ))) Also, you can use the '''Allocations''' dialog box to track the order fulfillment. For each allocation line, the '''Related Document''' column contains the reference number of the document related to the current stage of the order fulfillment. ==Item Availability Calculation for the SA Order== The way the order quantity is reflected in the system depends on the availability calculation rule selected for the item class (of each item included in the order) on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. Generally, as the status of a sales order of the ''SA'' type changes, the order quantity updates the SO Allocated, Back Ordered, and On Hand total quantities, which are reflected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. For more information on item availability calculation in inventory, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Availability_Calculation|Availability Calculation]. ==Reserving Stock Items for Sales Orders (SO)== To ensure that your order will be fulfilled in a timely fashion, you can reserve the specified item quantities for the order (by marking them as allocated). On the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form, you can click a sales order line and view the item availability information at the bottom of the form. In a sales order of the ''SO'' type, you may want to reserve the requested quantity for a specific item or multiple items if this is required by your company policies or was requested by the customer. {br}
To allocate stock for a particular line of an ''SO'' order, you use the '''Allocations''' dialog box, which opens if you click the needed line and then click '''Allocations''' on the table toolbar of the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form. By using this dialog box, for sales orders of the ''SO'' type, you can select whether to reserve the requested quantities of the item in a single warehouse or multiple warehouses. If subitems are used in your system, you can split the item quantity between the available subitems. Also, you can use the '''Allocations''' dialog box to track the order fulfillment. For each allocation line, the '''Related Document''' column contains the reference number of the document related to the current stage of the order fulfillment. ((({S:Hint} If the ordered items are out of stock at the shipping warehouse but available at other warehouses, you can allocate the items in other warehouses, and fulfill the order by any number of transfer orders from other warehouses. For more details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_scn_Sale_with_Transfer|Processing Steps for a Sale with Transfer]. Alternatively, you can process a purchase from a vendor for the subsequent sale to get the sufficient quantity of ordered items directly for this sales order. For more information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Purchase_for_Sale|Processing Purchased Items for Sale]. ))) ==Item Availability Calculation for the SO Order== The way the order quantity is reflected in the system depends on the availability calculation rule selected for the item class (of each included item) on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. Generally, as the status of a sales order of the ''SO'' type changes, the order quantity updates the SO Prepared, SO Booked, SO Allocated, and On Hand total quantities, which are reflected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Create_Sale_Order|To Create a Sales Order (SO)] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Create_Sale_Order_SA|To Create a Sales Order with Automatic Allocation (SA)]

Shipping goods is the main part of the order fulfillment process. After the sales order has been entered and the goods have been picked for sending them to a customer, you process a shipment. This chapter of the guide includes an overview of shipment processing in Acumatica ERP. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#table_hjd_ydl_ldb] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#ul_ijd_ydl_ldb] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_ShCreation|Shipment Creation Rules] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipment_Processing|Shipment Processing Steps] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipment_Process_Variations|Shipment Process Variations] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipping_Rules|Shipping Rule Combinations] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Partial_Shipments|Partial Shipping of Orders] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_ReplanBackOrders|Back Ordering and Replanning Back Orders]
| [anchor|#ul_jjd_ydl_ldb] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Create_Shipment|To Create a Shipment for an Order] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Process_Multiple_TRs|To Create Shipments for Multiple Orders] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Confirm_Shipment|To Confirm a Shipment] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Review_Shipment_for_TR|To Review a Shipment Prepared for an Order] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Replan_Back_Orders|To Replan Back Orders] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__How_Add_Orders_to_Shipment|To Add Sales Orders to a Shipment]
|}

Shipments, which are a key part of the order fulfillment process, can be incoming or outgoing. This topic discusses the outgoing shipments (based on the ''Issue'' operation) that are generated when a user processes a sale of items and ships the items to a customer; further we will refer to them as ''shipments''. The processing of incoming shipments (which are based on the ''Receipt'' operation, and thus are called receipts) involve customer returns based on return orders and is described in the topics of the [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Sale_Return|Processing Customer Returns] section. {br}
For a shipment prepared for a sales order, the typical processing involves the actions and generated documents shown in the following diagram. [anchor|#fig_pbz_bpd_h5][anchor|#image_zbv_1hn_dt][image:UserGuide/Images/Shipment_process.png|popup|Shipment process|300px] The following sections describe in detail the processing steps shown in the diagram.{br}{TOC} ==1. Prepare the Shipment== You can directly create a shipment document for a particular sales order on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form by selecting '''Actions''' > '''Create Shipment''' on the form toolbar; this brings up the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form with the new shipment document that includes the lines with items to be shipped. Alternatively, by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] form as a starting point, you can create a new shipment document and add one order or multiple orders of the same customer. {br}
To create multiple shipments for multiple sales orders of multiple customers, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_10_00|Process Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO501000|SO501000]) form. The system automatically assigns reference numbers to the created shipment documents, in accordance with the numbering sequence assigned to shipments on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form. {br}
If you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form to create shipments for a sales order that includes items to be shipped from multiple warehouses, you can create only one shipment at a time. Because an order with the ''Shipping'' status is read-only, there can be only one open shipment for the order from a particular warehouse. Once you confirm the open shipment, you can create a shipment to be sent from another warehouse. However, by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_10_00|Process Orders] form, you can create multiple shipments for these orders at once. ==2. Print the Pick List== You can print a pick list for a particular shipment by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form. For multiple shipments with the ''On Hold'' or ''Open'' status, you can print pick lists by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form. For more details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipment_Processing|Shipment Processing Steps]. ==3. Confirm the Shipment== After all the required goods are picked and packed, you can confirm the shipment by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Confirm Shipment''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form. You can confirm multiple shipments by executing the ''Confirm Shipment'' action for the selected shipments on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form. Shipment confirmation updates the available quantities and changes the status of the associated sales order. During shipment confirmation, the system checks that for all items for which lot or serial numbers are tracked, the appropriate numbers were specified. ==4. Print Shipment Confirmation== If authorization is required before the shipment is confirmed, you can print a shipment confirmation document to be signed by the authorized person by clicking '''Reports &gt; Print Shipment Confirmation''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form. For multiple shipments, you can print shipment confirmations by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form.{br}
To complete the sale, you must generate Sales Orders invoices and inventory issues and release these documents. The general workflow for most organizations is to first generate Sales Orders invoices and then release them; on release of these invoices, inventory issues are generated automatically. Another shipment processing workflow, in which an organization updates inventory and processes inventory issues before generating and processing customer invoices, is described in [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipment_Process_Variations|Shipment Process Variations]. ==5. Correct the Shipment== If you need to correct a shipment that has already been confirmed, click '''Actions''' > '''Correct Shipment''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form to reopen the shipment and make the required corrections. The associated order's status is changed to ''Shipping'' once you reopen the shipment. {br}
If an order that has a confirmed shipment has been canceled, you can reopen the order by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Re-Open Order''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. You can then delete or correct the shipment by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] form.{br}
If a shipment includes a sales order line that is also included in any subsequent shipments, you have to correct the subsequent shipments prior to correcting the preceding one. After you have completed all needed corrections, you can confirm the shipment or shipments that you have reopened. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_10_00|Process Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO501000|SO501000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_55_00|Assignment and Approval Maps] ([~/?ScreenId=EP205500|EP205500])

Due to shipment policies, your organization may process customer invoices later than it does inventory issues. In this case, you can first create issues, then generate invoices, and finally release invoices and issues. {br}
The processing of a sales order with issues created before invoices includes the steps and generated documents shown in the following diagram.[anchor|#_683df3df-3a3b-481f-b818-b16a5aa8c616][image:UserGuide/Images/Inventory_Sale_with_Issuing_Before_Invoicing.png|popup|450px] The following sections describe in detail the processing steps shown in the diagram.{br}{TOC} ==1. Enter the Sales Order== You create a new sales order is created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. If the order is created with the ''On Hold'' status, you should clear the '''Hold''' check box for the order to process it further. For details on the settings to be specified in the order, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_SO_OrderInfo|Sales Order Entry]. ==2. Prepare and Confirm the Shipment== For a particular order, you can create a shipment by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Create Shipment''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. Then you need to confirm the shipment. For more details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipment_Processing|Shipment Processing Steps]. ==3. Update Inventory== To manually create the inventory issue for a shipment, you can click '''Actions''' > '''Create Shipment''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form, or you can create inventory issues for multiple selected shipments by executing the ''Update IN'' action on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form. ==4. Release the Inventory Issue== To release the inventory issue (and thus, to update the item availability information in inventory), you click '''Actions &gt; Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]) form. When the inventory issue is released, the batch of General Ledger transactions is generated. ==5. Process the Sales Orders Invoice== You can prepare a Sales Orders (SO) invoice for a particular order by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Prepare Invoice''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_20_00|Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO302000|SO302000]) form, or you can create invoices for multiple selected shipments by executing the ''Prepare Invoice'' action on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_30_00|Process Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=SO503000|SO503000]) form. {br}
To release the SO invoice, you click '''Actions &gt; Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_30_00|Invoices] ([~/?ScreenId=SO303000|SO303000]) form after reviewing its details. When the SO invoice is released, the batch of General Ledger transactions is generated. {br}
To adjust the dates in the invoices generated for confirmed shipments, you can use the '''Use Shipment Date for Invoice Date''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form as follows:[anchor|#ul_trq_kjl_gdb] *Select this check box to set the shipment date as the invoice date. *Clear the check box to use the current business date as the default date for the invoice.

The shipping rules specified for a particular sales order define how the goods in the sales order should be shipped—whether they should be shipped only in full or partial shipments for the available quantities are allowed. The shipment rules for a sales order are applied when you create a shipment for a single order—by using the '''Create Shipment''' action on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form—or mass-create shipments for multiple orders, by running the '''Create Shipments''' process from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_10_00|Process Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO501000|SO501000]) form.{br}{TOC} ==Shipping Rule Options== On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form, you can specify the document-level shipping rule for the sales order document as a whole (in the '''Shipping Rule''' box on the '''Shipping Settings''' tab) and for each sales order line (in the '''Shipping Rule''' column on the '''Document Details''' tab). {br}
You can specify any of the following shipping rule options for order lines and for orders:[anchor|#ul_lmx_p53_zs] *''Ship Complete'' * ''Cancel Remainder'' * ''Back Order Allowed''
The shipping rules applied to order lines are explained in the following table.[anchor|#table_v1d_3q3_zs] ===Line-Level Shipping Rules=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="25%" ! Shipping Rule Option !width="75%" ! Result |- | '''Ship Complete''' | If a negative quantity is not allowed for the item specified in the line, the item can be included in a shipment only if the full ordered quantity is available for shipping. If the quantity of the item that is available for shipping is less than the ordered quantity, then the item in this line is not included in the shipment. The ordered quantity is shown as the '''Open Quantity''', and the line remains ''Open''. {br}
If shipping of the negative stock is allowed for the order type—that is, if '''Ship in Full If Negative Stock Is Allowed''' is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_20_10_00|Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=SO201000|SO201000]) form—the items for which a negative quantity is allowed are included in a shipment in the full ordered quantity, regardless of whether this quantity is available for shipping. (This rule does not apply to lot- or serial-tracked stock items.){br}
After this shipment has been confirmed, the line has the ''Completed'' status on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form. For details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Shipments|Shipment of Ordered Items]. |- | '''Cancel Remainder''' | With this shipping rule, shipping for the line is performed only once.{br}
If a negative quantity is not allowed for the item specified in the line, the item can be included in a shipment if any nonzero quantity that is less than or equal to the ordered quantity is available for shipping.{br}
If shipping of the negative stock is allowed for the order type, the items for which a negative quantity is allowed are included in a shipment in the full ordered quantity, regardless of whether it is available for shipping. (This rule does not apply to lot- or serial-tracked stock items.){br}
After this shipment has been confirmed, the line is marked as ''Completed'', and the '''Open Quantity''' value is set to zero.((({S:Hint}If you reopen a sales order line for which at least one shipment has been performed, the system changes the shipping rule to ''Back-Order Allowed'' for this line on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form. ))) |- | '''Back Order Allowed''' | If a negative quantity is not allowed for the item specified in the line, the item can be included in a shipment if any nonzero quantity that is less than or equal to the ordered quantity is available for shipping. The remaining quantity (if applicable) is shown as the '''Open Quantity''' on the line. The ordered quantity can be shipped in multiple shipments. The line gets the ''Completed'' status once the full ordered quantity has been shipped.{br}
If shipping of the negative stock is allowed for the order type, the items for which a negative quantity is allowed are included in a shipment in the full ordered quantity, regardless of whether the full quantity is available for shipping. (This rule does not apply to lot- or serial-tracked stock items.) After this shipment has been confirmed, the line has the ''Completed'' status.{br}
If shipping of the negative stock is not allowed for an order type, but you don&rsquo;t want to rely completely on availability data for the classes of items for which negative quantity is allowed, select the '''Add Zero Lines for Items Not in Stock''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] form. Then in the orders of this type, for order lines with the '''Back Order Allowed''' shipping rule, a zero-quantity line is added to the shipment if the item is not in stock; you can manually enter the actually available quantity of the item. |} See the table below for details about how the shipping rule of a sales order affects the mass-processing of the sales orders, which you perform by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_50_10_00|Process Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO501000|SO501000]) form. ((({S:Hint}If you initiate shipment creation for an individual sales order (by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] form) and the system detects a shortage of the items, the system displays the message informing you that the order cannot be shipped in full so that you can make an appropriate decision on the fulfillment of this order and change the quantities, create a partial shipment, or change the order status to ''Back Order'' manually. )))[anchor|#table_wl1_22h_ys] ===Document-Level Shipping Rules === {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="25%" ! Document-Level Rule !width="75%" ! Result |- | '''Ship Complete''' | If shipping cannot be performed for each line of the order, no shipment is created, and the order is assigned the ''Back Order'' status.{br}
The shipment is created (and the order is assigned the ''Shipping'' status) if shipping can be performed for each line—that is, if the lines meet the following criteria:[anchor|#ul_np3_vrj_zs] *For each ''Ship Complete'' line: The ordered quantity is available for shipping and can be shipped in full. *For each ''Cancel Remainder'' line: Any nonzero quantity that is equal to or less than the ordered quantity is available for shipping. *For each ''Back Order Allowed'' line: Any nonzero quantity that is equal to or less than the ordered quantity is available for shipping.
You cannot specify different '''Requested On''' dates for different lines in the order. {br}
When the shipment has been confirmed, the order is assigned the ''Completed'' status if all the lines have the ''Completed'' status. If any line is not completed, the order is assigned the ''Back Order'' status. |- | '''Cancel Remainder''' | If shipping cannot be performed for any of order lines, no shipment is created, and the order is assigned the ''Back Order'' status.{br}
If full or partial shipping can be performed for at least one line (according to the line&rsquo;s shipping rule), the shipment is created.{br}
You cannot specify different '''Requested On''' dates for different lines in the order. {br}
When the shipment has been confirmed, the order is assigned the ''Completed'' status if at least one line has the ''Completed'' status and the lines not included in shipment have the ''Cancel Remainder'' rule. The order is assigned the ''Back Order'' status if at least one line is not completed (that is, if it has a nonzero open quantity). |- | ''' Back Order Allowed''' | If shipping cannot be performed for any of the order lines, no shipment is created, and the order is assigned the ''Back Order'' status.{br}
You can specify different '''Requested On''' dates for different lines in the order, and different lines will be shipped on different dates. ((({S:Hint}If you change the '''Requested On''' date for the order, the system prompts you to choose whether you want to keep the dates specified for each line or to update the respective dates with the new '''Requested On''' date. ))){br}
If full or partial shipping can be performed for at least one line according to the line&rsquo;s shipping rule, the shipment is created. After the shipment has been confirmed, the order is assigned the ''Back Order'' status if other lines are not completed. |} ==Examples of the Application of Shipping Rules== The table below presents the examples that illustrate how the shipping rules specified for the sales order and its lines affect the fulfillment of the order. Assume this order has the following lines: [anchor|#ul_ccy_db1_bt] *Line 1: ''Product 1'' with an ordered quantity of 150 *Line 2: ''Product 2'' with an ordered quantity of 100
