==Notes About the Procedure==[anchor|#_0da0e505-362b-4c7f-a4bc-bbc8831eb3f9] The notes in this section describe the nuances of the UI elements available on the form, such as when an element is required and when it is not, and when the system fills in settings by default. This section can include other notes.{br}
Note the following about linking lines of Accounts Payable bills to purchase receipt lines:[anchor|#ul_lqk_24v_tz] *To be able to link the lines of a bill to the lines of a corresponding purchase receipt, make sure that for the bill the ''Tax Settings'' option is selected in the '''Tax Calculation Mode''' box on the '''Financial Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form. *You can link a bill line to only one line of a purchase receipt. If you have received only a partial quantity of an item, you can link the purchase receipt with the remaining quantity to another bill&rsquo;s line. *Information about the related documents appears for each linked line of the bill on the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] form (in the '''PO Type''', '''PO Number''', '''PO Receipt Nbr.''', and '''PO Receipt Line''' columns). While the bill is unreleased, you can cancel the established links and link the bill lines to other documents if needed.

The purchase price variance (PPV) amount is the difference between an item&rsquo;s actual unit cost on a purchase receipt (calculated as the item extended cost divided by its quantity) and its actual unit cost on a bill (calculated as the extended cost divided by the quantity on the bill) multiplied by the quantity of the item on the bill. ((({S:Hint} In Acumatica ERP, on purchase orders, purchase receipts, inventory receipts, and bills, the purchase prices of items are referred to as ''costs''. ))) The difference may occur due to various reasons, such as exchange rate fluctuations or unplanned changes in the vendor price or delivery costs. Different businesses may use different approaches when accounting for the purchase price variance amounts. The topic describes the options available in Acumatica ERP for allocation of the purchase price variance amounts for stock items.{br}{TOC} ==PPV Calculation== Generally, the actual vendor prices and discounts may change frequently, and when you enter a purchase receipt on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form and specify an item by its inventory ID, the exact vendor price and applicable discounts are not known. Even if the unit cost appears automatically in the '''Unit Cost''' column, you can manually enter only the item quantity and the extended cost (which may include the vendor&rsquo;s current promotional price and discount for the specified quantity not yet configured in the system); the extended cost will not be recalculated based on the unit cost. For the PPV calculation, the system will use the actual unit cost (calculated as the extended amount per unit), not the unit cost that is available in the system and was inserted automatically. {br}
When you enter a related bill by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form, you know the prices and any additional costs, and you can reflect them on the bill. On release of a bill that is linked to the purchase receipt, the system calculates the purchase price variance amount for each line item as follows:[anchor|#ul_hnx_yfs_4t] * Calculates the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the purchase receipt as the extended cost on the purchase receipt divided by the quantity * Calculates the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the bill as the extended cost on the bill divided by the quantity on the bill * Subtracts the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the bill from the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the receipt * Multiplies the difference by the quantity on the bill
For example, the following documents (a purchase receipt and the AP bill linked to the receipt) were entered into the system.[anchor|#table_kry_w4s_4t] ===Receipt Details=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="33%" ! Item !width="33%" ! Quantity !width="33%" ! Extended Cost |- | New Item1 | 20 | 4500 |- | New Item2 | 30 | 9000 |}[anchor|#table_nl5_3ps_4t] ===Bill Details=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="33%" ! Item !width="33%" ! Quantity !width="33%" ! Extended Cost |- | New Item1 | 10 | 2000 |- | New Item2 | 30 | 9900 |}{br}
The PPV amounts are calculated as follows:[anchor|#table_wth_gqs_4t] ===PPV Calculation=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="33%" ! Item !width="33%" ! Quantity !width="33%" ! PPV |- | New Item1 | 10 | 250 |- | New Item2 | 30 | -900 |} The ways the calculated PPV amounts can be allocated depend on the item valuation method and the selected allocation mode and are described in the following sections. ==PPV Allocation for Exchange Rate Changes== By default, in a purchase receipt, the system inserts the currency rate that is current on the purchase receipt date. If needed, you can override the default currency rate if all of the following are true:[anchor|#_4917e597-18d0-4813-a652-0f68e58d618a] *The ''Multi-Currency Accounting'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. *The '''Change Currency Rate on Receipt''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. *The '''Enable Rate Override''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] ([~/?ScreenId=AP303000|AP303000]) form for the vendor specified in the purchase receipt.
The system will use the new exchange rate for calculating the unit cost of the items in the inventory receipt that it creates on release of the current purchase receipt. {br}
On release of an AP bill that is linked to this purchase receipt, the system calculates the purchase price variance amount for each line item as follows:[anchor|#_083759b9-30af-4012-8934-821fb782dd0e] *Calculates the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the purchase receipt based on the exchange rate of the purchase receipt * Calculates the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the bill based on the exchange rate of the bill * Subtracts the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the bill from the unit&rsquo;s actual cost on the receipt * Multiplies the difference by the quantity on the bill
==PPV Allocation for Items with Standard Costs== For stock items with ''Standard'' assigned as the cost valuation method on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, any PPV amounts are allocated to the Purchase Price Variance account defined by the posting class of the item. For more information, see the '''Standard Cost Valuation Method''' section of the [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods] topic. ==PPV Allocation Modes for Items with Other Valuation Methods== In Acumatica ERP, you can select how you want to process the purchase price variance amounts for stock items with the following valuation methods: ''Average'', ''FIFO'', or ''Specific''. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form, you can select one of the following modes of PPV allocation:[anchor|#ul_l14_yys_hs] *''Inventory Account'': To record the variance to the inventory accounts to update the item costs. If you select this mode, you also need to select the reason code (in the adjacent box) that will provide the expense accounts and subaccounts used for the allocation of the PPV amounts. *''Purchase Price Variance Account'': To record any variance amounts to the purchase price variance accounts to be further processed as additional expenses.
The modes of PPV allocation are discussed in detail in the sections below. ==The Inventory Account Mode of PPV Allocation== If the ''Inventory Account'' mode is selected as the mode of PPV allocation, on release of a bill, an inventory adjustment for the PPV amounts is generated automatically. You can view the reference number of the adjustment in the '''PPV Ref. Nbr.''' column on the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] form.{br}
Consider a few scenarios that may occur with a received stock item (with no lot or serial numbers) when the bill is released:[anchor|#ul_iq1_trt_hs] *If no units of the item have been issued from a warehouse since the item was received, this adjustment debits the inventory account of the item for the positive variance amount and credits the PO Accrual account (or credits the inventory account for the negative amount and debits the PO Accrual account for the same amount). See [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_PPV_Scenario1|Purchase Price Variance Allocation: Example 1]. *If all the units of the item have been issued from a warehouse before the bill has been created and an adjustment has been generated, this adjustment debits the variance amount to the expense account associated with the reason code. *If some (but not all) of the units of the item have been issued from the warehouse, the adjustment distributes the variance amount proportionally between the quantity of units issued and the quantity of units still in the warehouse, and allocates the respective amounts to the expense account (associated with the reason code) and to the inventory account. For details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_PPV_Scenario2|Purchase Price Variance Allocation: Example 2]. *:((({S:Hint}If multiple bills are created for partial quantities of items from a receipt and certain quantities of the items (from that receipt) have been issued from the warehouse, the PPV amounts on each adjustment generated for a partial bill are allocated between the inventory accounts and the expense accounts in the same proportion in which the original quantities from the receipt are distributed between the quantities issued and the quantities still in stock. ))) ((({S:Hint}If a PPV adjustment would result in negative balance of the inventory account, the adjustment amount is posted to the expense account. ))) If you need to reverse the bill linked to the receipt, you can do this only if the adjustment has been released. On reversal of the bill, no new adjustment is created to revert the original adjustment—the original adjustment remains in the system. If you then create a second bill for the same purchase receipt, the system generates a new adjustment that adjusts the first (original) adjustment. ==The Purchase Price Variance Account Mode of PPV Allocation== If ''Purchase Price Variance Account'' is selected as the mode of PPV allocation, on release of a bill, the entire PPV amount is recorded to the Purchase Price Variance account defined by the posting class of the item. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_PPV_Scenario1|Purchase Price Variance Allocation: Example 1] *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_PPV_Scenario2|Purchase Price Variance Allocation: Example 2]

The type of purchasing transaction for which a buyer pays at the time of delivery is generally referred to as ''cash on delivery (COD)'' or, because other methods of payment besides cash might be involved, ''collect on delivery (COD)''. Acumatica ERP provides you with functionality that you can use to account for payments made on delivery. {br}
This topic describes the basic workflow when you process a purchase order to be paid on delivery. ==Basic Process== To process a purchase order that will be paid on delivery, you perform the following general steps:[anchor|#ol_zqc_nxg_bq] #''Create a purchase order.'' #:On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form, create a purchase order. Select the vendor, and provide all the required details about the goods and services to be purchased. Save the order. #:((({S:Hint}Depending on your company&rsquo;s policies, additional steps might follow the creation of the purchase order—for instance, for approval of the order. ))) #''Create a prepayment request linked to the purchase order.'' #:While you are viewing the purchase order, on the '''Actions''' menu, select ''Create Prepayment''. The system opens the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form, with information filled in for a new prepayment request from the purchase order; the reference number of the purchase order is shown in the '''Vendor Ref.''' box. Save the prepayment request. For more details, see [HelpRoot_Financials\AP__how_Entering_a_Prepayment|To Enter a Prepayment]. Release the prepayment request. #:((({S:Hint}An unreleased prepayment request is synchronized with a purchase order as follows: If you edit the details of the purchase order, the prepayment request is changed accordingly. ))) #:Open the purchase order on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form, and make sure that the reference number of the prepayment request is shown in the '''Prepayment Ref. Nbr.''' box. #''Prepare an AP check''. #:On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form, open the prepayment request, and click ''Pay Bill/Apply Adjustment'' on the '''Actions''' menu. This action opens the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_20_00|Checks and Payments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP302000|AP302000]) form with information filled in for a new AP check, which is ready to be saved. Save and release the check. For more details, see [HelpRoot_Financials\AP__how_Creating_an_AP_Check|To Create an Accounts Payable Check]. #''Create a receipt for the purchase order''. #:Once the goods are received and payment is made, you can create a receipt in either of the following ways: #*On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form, open the original purchase order. On the''' Actions''' menu, select '''Create Receipt'''. This opens the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form with a ready-to-save receipt. #*On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form, specify the vendor, and on the table toolbar of the '''Details''' tab, click '''Add PO'''. Select the original purchase order to add to the receipt. #:Save the receipt. #''Release the receipt.'' #: On release of the receipt, the system generates an AP bill, applies prepayment to the purchase order, and changes the status of the purchase order to ''Closed''.
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000])

 Acumatica ERP supports four purchase order types: normal, drop ship, blanket, and standard. For all these types, the same set of statuses is used; however, different processing steps can be configured for purchase orders of different types. {br}

The purchasing process usually starts when you create a purchase order in Acumatica ERP on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form. You can add goods to the purchase order and specify the details for each line. The system changes the status of the purchase order during its processing. {br}

The following table describes each of the possible statuses and the ways they fit into purchase order processing; the statuses are listed in the order in which they occur, if applicable. [anchor|#table_cpp_fxt_mt]
{| class="checklist" | width="100%" 
|- 
!width="20%" ! Status
!width="80%" ! Description
|- 
| ''On Hold''
| 
A newly created purchase order that does not originate from a change order has a status of ''On Hold''. The system may also assign the purchase order this status if it has been rejected by the person assigned to approve it or if you have selected the '''Hold''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form. The purchase order can be left on hold for future editing, including the addition or removal of lines.{br}

If a purchase order has a line related to a project with the change order workflow enabled, you can select the '''Hold''' check box only if the purchase order has the ''Rejected'' status. You cannot select the '''Hold''' check box for a purchase order that has at least one related change order. For more information about change orders, see [HelpRoot_Projects\PM__con_Change_Management|Change Management].{br}

When a purchase order is on hold, its totals and quantities of listed goods are not traced or checked. To move the ''On Hold ''purchase order to the next step in its processing and change its status, you clear the '''Hold''' check box. You can turn on the validation of totals for purchase orders of specific types by selecting the relevant check boxes in the '''Validate Total on Entry''' section on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. This validation (if it is turned on for purchase orders of the specific type) is performed when you clear the '''Hold''' check box for the order.{br}

 Whether or not validation is performed, when you clear this check box, the system changes the status of the purchase order to ''Pending Approval'', ''Pending Printing'', ''Pending Email'', or ''Open'', depending on the purchase order approval rules specified in the system and your required processing steps.
|- 
| ''Pending Approval''
| 
Depending on your organization&rsquo;s approval rules for purchase orders as defined in Acumatica ERP, the status of a purchase order might be changed to ''Pending Approval'' after the '''Hold''' check box has been cleared. This status indicates that the purchase order requires approval. This status remains until all required approvals have been performed.{br}

To approve a purchase order with this status, an authorized user selects '''Actions''' > '''Approve''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form. When the user performing the last (or only) required approval invokes this action, the system changes its status to ''Pending Printing'', ''Pending Email'', or ''Open''.{br}

To reject a purchase order with this status, an authorized user selects '''Actions''' > '''Reject''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form. When this user invokes this action, the system changes its status to ''Rejected''.
|- 
| ''Rejected''
| 
Depending on your organization&rsquo;s approval rules for purchase orders as defined in Acumatica ERP, the status of a purchase order might be changed to ''Rejected'' after an employee who was assigned to approve the purchase order has rejected it.{br}

You can save a purchase order with the ''Rejected'' status with the ''On Hold'' status for further editing by selecting the '''Hold''' check box.
|- 
| ''Pending Printing''
| 
Printing a purchase order is an optional step in purchase order processing that is performed if the vendor prefers to receive printed purchase orders by fax or postal mail. Depending on the vendor settings, the status of the purchase order may be changed to ''Pending Printing'' from ''On Hold'' or ''Pending Approval'' to ''Pending Printing''. To require printing in the purchase order processing steps for a particular vendor, you select the '''Print Order''' check box on the '''Purchase Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] ([~/?ScreenId=AP303000|AP303000]) form. The '''Printed''' check box on the '''Other Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form shows whether the order has been printed.{br}

A newly created purchase order that originates from a change order is assigned the ''Pending Printing'' status if the vendor&rsquo;s settings require the printing of purchase orders. The system also assigns the ''Pending Printing'' status to a purchase order if the vendor&rsquo;s settings require the printing of purchase orders and the purchase order, which had the ''Open'' status, has been changed by means of change orders.{br}

The ''Pending Printing'' status indicates that an employee must print the purchase order and then send or fax it to the vendor. To print the purchase order, you select '''Reports''' > '''Print Purchase Order''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form. This changes the status of the purchase order to ''Pending Email'' or ''Open''.
|- 
| ''Pending Emai''l
| 
Emailing a purchase order to the vendor is an optional step in purchase order processing that is performed if the vendor prefers to receive purchase orders by email. Depending on the vendor settings, the status of the purchase order may be changed to ''Pending Email'' from ''On Hold'', ''Pending Approval'', or ''Pending Printing''. To require emailing in the purchase order processing steps for a particular vendor, select the '''Email Order''' check box on the '''Purchase Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_30_00|Vendors] form. The '''Emailed''' check box on the '''Other Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form shows whether the order has been emailed.{br}

A newly created purchase order that originates from a change order is assigned the ''Pending Email'' status if the vendor&rsquo;s settings require the emailing of purchase orders. The system also assigns the ''Pending Email'' status to a purchase order if the vendor&rsquo;s settings require the emailing of purchase orders and the purchase order, which had the ''Open'' status, has been changed by means of change orders.{br}

When a purchase order has the ''Pending Email'' status, the purchase order must be sent by email to the vendor. To complete this step, you select '''Actions''' > '''Email Purchase Order''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form. This changes the order status to ''Open''.
|- 
| ''Canceled''
| 
The status of the purchase order is changed to ''Canceled'' if the purchase order has been canceled by a user selecting '''Actions''' > '''Cancel Order''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form. This status means the purchase order cannot be edited, and no receipts can be created for it.{br}

The canceled purchase order keeps this status unless you change the status to ''On Hold'' by selecting the '''Hold''' check box for it. If the status is changed to ''On Hold'', the document can be edited, and the usual purchase order processing steps can be performed.
|- 
| ''Open''
| 
The status of the purchase order is changed to ''Open'' after any necessary approvals and any other required processing steps (printing the order, emailing it, or both) have been performed for the purchase order. If no approvals or optional processing steps are required, the status of the purchase order changes from ''On Hold'' to ''Open'' when the '''Hold''' check box is cleared.{br}

A newly created purchase order that originates from a change order is assigned the ''Open'' status if the vendor&rsquo;s settings do not require the printing or emailing of purchase orders.{br}

The ''Open'' status means that the quantity of the items on purchase receipts for this purchase order is less than the quantity required to complete the purchase order. In Acumatica ERP, you create the receipts for the ordered and received items by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form.{br}

When a purchase order has the ''Open'' status, the system traces the quantities of items received for the order and displays the item availability information on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form in accordance with the availability calculation rule assigned to the item class to which the item belongs. This rule is specified for the item class in the '''Availability Calculation Rule''' box on the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form.
|- 
| ''Closed''
| 
The status of the purchase order is changed from ''Open'' to ''Closed'' after all the lines of the order have been completed according to the appropriate rules or manually. Also, you can manually complete the order by selecting '''Actions''' > '''Complete Order''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] form.{br}

For more information about order fulfillment, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Purchase_Order_Processing|Purchase Order Creation].
|}

In most cases, the purchasing process is completed when goods are received, and Accounts Payable bills are released to adjust your outstanding balance with the vendor. In some cases, however, items that have been delivered in an unsatisfactory condition or shipped by mistake should be returned to the vendor for replacement or reimbursement. Also, services that were not rendered or were provided partially should be reimbursed.{br}
This topic describes the general workflow of processing purchase returns in Acumatica ERP. {br}{TOC} ==Processing a Purchase Return== To process a vendor return, you create a document of the ''Return'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form. You can select particular lines of the needed purchase receipt and create a return with these items. Alternatively, you can create a new purchase return and add any number of purchase receipts or individual purchase receipt lines to it by clicking '''Add PR''' or '''Add PR Line''' on the table toolbar of the '''Document Details''' tab. In the added lines, you can change the quantity of items to be returned.{br}
You can create purchase returns for purchase receipts, whether or not they are linked to a purchase order. For lines that are linked to a purchase order, you can select the '''Open PO Line''' check box in purchase return lines on the '''Document Details''' tab to specify that the system should change the status of the related purchase order to ''Open'' on release of the return (if you want to keep the purchase order open until the replacement items are received). If the '''Open PO Line''' check box is cleared, the related purchase order remains closed.{br}
You can process returns for purchase receipt lines with stock and non-stock items. For stock items, you must specify the warehouse and warehouse location from which the items will be issued to be sent back to the vendor. For items with lot or serial numbers, you can click '''Allocations''' on the table toolbar of the '''Document Details''' tab to specify these numbers for the returned units. For each line in the return receipt, a reason code must be specified. By default, the system specifies the reason code that is selected in the '''PO Return Reason Code''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. For vendor returns, a reason code with the ''Vendor Return'' usage type should be used.((({S:Hint}For processing returns at the calculated cost, you can also use a reason code with the ''Issue'' usage type, but these reason codes are not applicable for processing returns at the original receipt cost. ))) When a user processes a purchase return, the related inventory document (inventory adjustment or inventory issue) and accounts payable debit adjustment are generated. On release of the inventory document, the quantities of returned items are deducted from the item quantities available at the specified warehouse locations. If the purchase receipt for which the return was created is linked to a purchase order, the '''Qty. On Receipts''' in the purchase order is decreased by the quantity of returned items. The further processing of returns depends on the agreement between your company and the vendor. You can complete the processing of the return in the Accounts Payable module by processing a vendor refund, or by receiving replacement items for the original purchase order.{br}
When creating a purchase return, you can process the items at the cost that was originally specified in the purchase receipt, or at the cost calculated according to the valuation method of the item. The remaining sections of this topic describe these two processes in more details. ==Processing a Return of Items at the Original Receipt Cost== The costs of items could change over time. To specify that items should be returned to inventory at exactly the same cost at which the items have been purchased, you need to select the '''Return by Original Receipt Cost''' check box in the purchase return document on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form.{br}
Once the purchase return is released, the system automatically generates an inventory adjustment that includes the stock items and non-stock items requiring receipt. Service lines (that is, lines with non-stock items that do not require receipt) are not included in the inventory adjustment. The reference number of the inventory adjustment generated for the purchase return is shown in the '''IN Ref. Nbr.''' box on the '''Other Information''' tab. The inventory adjustments that are generated for purchase returns are released immediately; when inventory adjustments are released, the availability data for the items in inventory is updated.{br}
For a line with a stock item, the following general ledger transactions are generated on release of an inventory adjustment:[anchor|#_c7d660f9-543c-4959-8d6a-077adda13b4e] *PO Accrual account and subaccount: Dr, original cost *Inventory account and subaccount: Cr, original cost
The original cost for stock items is defined by the following rules:[anchor|#_2c8f6a96-cc32-4e96-b778-feafd92f72a8] *For items with the FIFO valuation method, the system uses the average cost of the cost layer that corresponds to the purchase receipt for which the return is processed. *For items with the average, specific, and standard valuation methods, the system uses the cost specified in the line of the original inventory receipt or purchase receipt.
The cost adjustments, such as landed costs or purchase price variance are not included in the original cost.{br}
If the '''Create Bill''' check box is selected in the purchase return on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form, when you release the purchase return, the system generates an accounts payable debit adjustment to the vendor automatically. Otherwise, you need to prepare the bill manually by clicking '''Actions &gt; Enter AP Bill''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form. The generated AP debit adjustment is available on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form. {br}
The accounts payable debit adjustments are released immediately if the '''Release AP Documents Automatically''' option is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] form; otherwise, you should release these adjustments manually. {br}
On release of a debit adjustment, the following general ledger transactions are generated:[anchor|#_b4394948-f001-4da0-b5d4-a49e69c7fcaf] *Accounts Payable account and subaccount: Dr, original cost *PO Accrual account and subaccount: Cr, original cost
For return lines with stock items, on release of the AP debit adjustment prepared for the purchase return, the system records any PO Accrual difference to the Purchase Price Variance account and subaccount that are defined in the posting class of the stock item. ==Processing a Return of Items at the Cost Calculated by the System== If the '''Return by Original Receipt Cost''' check box is cleared in the purchase return document on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form, the system calculates the cost at which the item should be returned according to the item's valuation method.{br}
Once the purchase return is released, the system automatically generates an inventory issue that includes stock items and non-stock items requiring receipt. Service items (that is, non-stock items that do not require receipt) are not included in the inventory issue. The reference number of the inventory issue generated for a purchase return is shown in the '''IN Ref. Nbr.''' box on the '''Other Information''' tab. The inventory issues that are generated for returns are released immediately; once inventory issues are released, the availability data for the items in inventory is updated.{br}
On release of an inventory issue, the following general ledger transactions are generated:[anchor|#_d563f08b-5a99-4246-bee8-ac2b2b81c222] *PO Accrual account and subaccount: Dr, calculated cost *Inventory account and subaccount: Cr, calculated cost
The cost to be used in the lines of an inventory issue is calculated depending on the item&rsquo;s valuation method (for instance, for items with ''Average'' as the valuation method, it is the current unit cost calculated at the moment of release of the issue). {br}
For a line with a non-stock item requiring receipt, the following general ledger transactions are generated on release of an inventory issue:[anchor|#_157e8900-822a-4e30-a967-81028bb9ea14] *PO Accrual account of the posting class of the item: Dr, unit cost of the purchase return line *Expense account of the posting class of the item: Cr, unit cost of the purchase return line
If the '''Create Bill''' check box is selected in the purchase return on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form, when you release the purchase return, the system generates an accounts payable debit adjustment to the vendor automatically. Otherwise, you need to prepare the bill manually by clicking '''Actions &gt; Enter AP Bill''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] form. The generated AP debit adjustment is available on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form. {br}
The Accounts Payable debit adjustments are released immediately if the '''Release AP Documents Automatically''' option is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] form; otherwise, you should release these adjustments manually. {br}
On release of debit adjustment, the following general ledger transactions are generated:[anchor|#_0e2b3809-41d8-4904-896f-35a9e0a1f5a1] *Accounts Payable account of the vendor: Dr, calculated cost *PO Accrual account of the posting class of the item: Cr, calculated cost
On release of the AP debit adjustment prepared for the purchase return, the system records any PO Accrual difference to the Purchase Price Variance account and subaccount that are defined in the posting class of the stock item. ==Processing a Return of Non-Stock Items Requiring Receipt== Purchase return lines with the ''Non-Stock'' line type are added to the inventory issue or adjustment generated on the release of the purchase return. On release of the inventory transaction, the following batch of general ledger transactions is generated: [anchor|#_2da62979-1fb0-441b-a0a0-d2a921bf43cc] *PO Accrual account of the purchase return line: Dr, unit cost of the purchase return line *Expense account of the purchase return line: Cr, unit cost of the purchase return line
On release of debit adjustment, the following General Ledger transactions are generated:[anchor|#_a7a58688-0d95-4085-9f66-2ca19fca3f75] *Accounts Payable account of the vendor: Dr, calculated cost *PO Accrual account of the purchase return line: Cr, calculated cost
On release of the AP debit adjustment prepared for the purchase return, the system records any PO Accrual difference based on the '''Allocation Mode''' selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form as follows:[anchor|#_be8df457-ca2b-48f9-b7b4-613545732aeb] *If ''Purchase Price Variance Account'' is selected, the system posts the PO Accrual difference to the Purchase Price Variance account and subaccount specified in the posting class of the item. *If ''Inventory Account'' is selected, the system posts the PO Accrual difference to the Expense account and subaccount specified in the related purchase return line.
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Purchase_Receipt_Processing|Purchase Receipt Creation] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000])

With Acumatica ERP, your company can track the landed costs incurred for purchased or transferred stock items, to accurately calculate the total costs of the items. Landed costs in Acumatica ERP are processed through landed cost documents. In a landed cost document, you specify the landed cost amounts, and the purchase receipts or transfer receipts, to which these landed cost amounts should be allocated. {br}{TOC} ==General Workflow and Related Documents== You can add to a single landed cost document either purchase receipts or transfer receipts (but not both types). The type of the added receipts does not affect the landed cost document workflow. The diagram below shows the processing steps for landed cost documents.[anchor|#_53a0eda2-c0f0-4b05-8770-62e7247e53b3][anchor|#_02578cd5-5d6c-4514-b39d-bff4d0f26b40][image:UserGuide/Images/LC_Process.png|popup|450px] The following sections describe in detail the processing steps shown in the diagram. ==1. Enter the Landed Cost Document== You create a new landed cost document on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_30_00|Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO303000|PO303000]) form. The reference number for the new landed cost document is generated in accordance with the numbering sequence specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. If the landed cost document is created with the ''On Hold'' status, you should clear the '''Hold''' check box for the document before releasing it. ==2. Add Receipt Lines to which Landed Costs Will Be Allocated== You add the documents or particular document lines for which the landed costs were incurred by clicking '''Add PO Receipt''' or '''Add PO Receipt Line''' on the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_30_00|Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO303000|PO303000]) form. You then select the unlabeled check boxes in the rows of the needed lines in the dialog box that opens, and click '''Add&Close''' to add the selected lines. You can add the lines of either purchase receipts or transfer receipts to a landed cost document. ==3. Specify Landed Cost Codes and Amounts== You add the landed costs to be allocated between the added receipt lines by adding the landed cost code and specifying the amount to be allocated on the '''Landed Costs''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_30_00|Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO303000|PO303000]) form. ==4. Release the Landed Cost Document== To release the prepared landed cost document, you click '''Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_30_00|Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO303000|PO303000]) form. Alternatively, you can release multiple landed cost documents at the same time by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_50_60_00|Release Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO506000|PO506000]) form. {br}
When the landed cost document is released, the system automatically generates a corresponding inventory adjustment (one for each landed cost code) to update the cost of items in inventory. You can view the generated inventory adjustment on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=IN303000|IN303000]) form. ==5. Release the Inventory Adjustment== The generated inventory adjustment is released automatically if the '''Release LC IN Adjustments Automatically''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. If this check box is cleared, you have to release the inventory adjustment manually by clicking '''Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=IN303000|IN303000]) form. {br}
On release of the inventory adjustment, a batch of GL transactions is generated. The costs of inventory items are updated according to the items&rsquo; valuation methods, as described in the [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Updating_Cost_by_LC|Adding Landed Costs to Items' Costs]. ==6. Prepare the Accounts Payable Bill== If the '''Create Bill''' check box is selected in the landed cost document on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_30_00|Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO303000|PO303000]) form, when you release the landed cost document, the system generates an AP bill to the landed cost vendor automatically. {br}
Otherwise, you need to prepare the bill from the purchase receipt by clicking '''Actions &gt; Enter AP Bill''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form. Alternatively, you can create a new AP bill manually on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form and add or link the lines of the landed cost document to the bill. For more information on the processing of AP bills, see [HelpRoot_Financials\AP_MNG_BillsAndAdjustments|Processing Bills and Adjustments].{br}
If the exact amount of the landed costs has changed, in the generated AP bill, you can manually adjust the amount of the landed costs. Any difference will be posted to dedicated accounts, as described in the [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_LC_Postponed|Adjusting the Landed Cost Variance]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Landed_Cost_Codes|Configuration of Landed Cost Codes]

Some landed costs, such as freight, are typically known when the goods are received. Other types of landed costs may become known later, when a bill from the service provider is received. When you need to enter the landed costs of a specific type in a landed cost document, if the exact amount of the landed costs is not known yet, you can enter the estimated amount for the appropriate landed cost code in the landed cost document on the '''Landed Costs''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_30_00|Landed Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=PO303000|PO303000]) tab. {br}
Later, when the exact amount becomes known, you can manually adjust the amount of the landed costs in the accounts payable bill generated for the landed cost document, and release the bill. The difference between the estimated amount and the adjusted amount is automatically added to the Landed Cost Variance account specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_20_00|Landed Cost Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=PO202000|PO202000]) form for the landed cost used on the original receipt. {br}
The following accounts are involved in the GL transactions that are generated on release of the AP bill to the landed cost vendor:[anchor|#_47388038-5957-4c9a-9aae-86ce280882c3] *Accounts Payable account of the landed cost vendor *Landed Cost Accrual account of the landed cost code *Landed Cost Variance account of the landed cost code
On release of the AP bill to the landed cost vendor, if the landed cost amount specified in the landed cost document hasn&rsquo;t been changed, the following general ledger transactions are posted:[anchor|#_f053a904-650d-4fa9-a144-2906891e82ea] *Accounts Payable account: Cr, landed cost amount *Landed Cost Accrual account: Dr, landed cost amount
On release of the AP bill to landed cost vendor, if the landed cost amount has been changed in the bill, the following general ledger transactions are posted:[anchor|#_b5b45459-974d-4bd0-b672-76b90a770cf1] *Accounts Payable account: Cr, bill amount *Landed Cost Accrual account: Cr, correction amount *Landed Cost Variance account of the landed cost code: Dr, correction amount *Landed Cost Accrual account: Dr, bill amount
For information on how the system allocates the landed cost variance for landed costs added to items&rsquo; cost, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Updating_Cost_by_LC|Adding Landed Costs to Items' Costs]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Landed_Cost_Tracking|Processing Landed Cost Documents]

To add line or lines of a landed cost document to an Accounts Payable bill to a landed cost vendor, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form. ==To Add a Landed Cost Line to Bill==[anchor|#_f4e37f8c-932d-4ef5-b91f-3d3304f2f4c3] #Open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_30_10_00|Bills and Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=AP301000|AP301000]) form by searching for or navigating to it. #:((({S:Hint}To open any form, you can navigate to it or search for it (by its name or by its form ID without periods). For more information about search capabilities, see [HelpRoot_Interface\UIG__con_New_UI_Search|Search in the Modern UI]. ))) #In the '''Type''' box, select ''Bill'', and select the needed bill by its reference number. #On the table toolbar of the '''Document Details''' tab, click '''Add LC'''. In the '''Add LC''' dialog box, which opens, do the following: ##Optional: Filter the lines in the table by selecting any of the following: the particular landed cost document in the '''LC Nbr.''' box, the particular receipt in the '''Receipt Nbr.''' box, or the particular landed cost code in the '''LC Code''' box. ##In the table, select the unlabeled check boxes in the line or lines with the landed costs to be added to the bill. ##Click '''Add & Close''' to close the dialog box and add the selected lines. #On the '''Document Details''' tab, review the added lines, and correct their '''Ext. Cost''', if needed. #On the form toolbar, click '''Save''' to save your changes.
